Practical exercise 23: Stratified analysis of cross tabulations

We will use the data from the study about oesophageal cancer. This data is stored in the BD2.SAV file. This file does not contain individual data but “tabulated” data. To use these data correctly the records have to be “weighted”.

Question a

Open the data set and inspect what this “tabulated” data looks like.

Code

bd2 <- read.spss("./data/Bd2.sav", to.data.frame = TRUE) # read the data and store
dim(bd2)       # What are the dimensions of the dataset? 
head(bd2)      # Print the first six rows of the data
summary(bd2)   # Summarizes the variables

Hints

In order to inspect the data frame, you can for example 1) look at the dimensions of the data frame (dim), 2) check the header of the data frame (head), or 3) summarize the data frame (summary).

Discussion

As you can see, this data frame consists of 4 columns and 22 rows. Every row contains a certain group of people, for example people who do not have oesophageal cancer, drink 0-79 grams of alcohol daily and are at least 75 years of age. The column “NUMBER” tells you how many people have these characteristics. Later on in this exercise, you will take into account that these numbers differ.

Question b

Find the (crude) odds ratio of alcohol use for oesophageal cancer.

Code

crosstab <- xtabs(bd2$NUMBER ~ bd2$ALC + bd2$DISEASE)
crosstab # to inspect what the cross tab looks like
odds.ratio(crosstab)

Hints

You can use the function xtabs() to make a cross table. In this xtabs() function define the variable that defines the exposure + the variable that defines the outcome, this will resemble the cross table from exercise 9c.
Because this data set contains tabulated data, you also need to take into account the numbers per group. You can include this weighting in the xtabs() function. The weighting variable plus the ~ symbol should be placed before the two variables you are interested in. For example: crosstab <- xtabs(data$NUMBERS ~ data$EXPOSURE + data$OUTCOME)

Subsequently, you can use the function odds.ratio() from the package samplesizeMCH to get the crude odds ratio.

Output

crosstab <- xtabs(bd2$NUMBER ~ bd2$ALC + bd2$DISEASE)  # create a table
crosstab # to inspect what the cross table looks like
##                       bd2$DISEASE
## bd2$ALC                control case
##   0-79 g alcohol daily     666  104
##   > 80 g alcohol daily     109   96
odds.ratio(crosstab) # the odds ratio 
## [1] 5.640085

Discussion

The crude odds ratio for oesophageal cancer in alcohol users versus non-alcohol users is 5.64. This means that individuals that are exposed to more than 80 gram alcohol daily have a 5.64 times higher odds to get oesophageal cancer compared to individuals that consume 0-79 gram alcohol on a daily basis.

Question c

Now we will examine this odds ratio in different age groups. To do so, create a three-dimensional cross table with age group as third variable.

Why does R give infinite (“Inf”) odds ratios of the first and last age group? What can you say about these odds ratios?
Write down the odds ratios that can be computed for the different age groups.

Code

crosstab_strat <- xtabs(bd2$NUMBER ~ bd2$ALC + bd2$DISEASE + bd2$AGEGR) # create a table
crosstab_strat  # print the cross table
apply(crosstab_strat, 3, odds.ratio) # use the apply function to get the OR

Hints

You can use the same xtabs() function for the three-dimensional cross table. The only thing you need to do, is add another variable after a + symbol.

To get the odds ratio for every age group separately, you can use the apply() function, which can apply a function (in this case retrieving the odds ratio) to multiple tables. For this apply() function, you need to define three arguments: apply(X, MARGIN, FUN).

  • X is the array you want to apply the function to, in this case your three-dimensional cross table.

  • MARGIN is telling the function what part of the array this function should be applied to - in this case you should define it as 3 because it should be applied to the whole tables.

  • FUN defines the function, in this case the function for retrieving the odds ratio.

    One of the cells of the cross tables of the lowest and highest age category contains the value 0. This makes it impossible to calculate an odds ratio and why R is printing “Inf”.

You can interpret the other values the same way. It is interesting to see that the odds ratio in the age group 65-74 is lower compared to the youngers ages.

    Question d

    Retrieve the Cochran’s and Mantel-Haenszel statistic and perform a test for homogeneity of the odds ratio.

  • Which null hypothesis is tested with “Conditional Independence” and which null hypothesis with “Homogeneity”? Explain the numbers of degrees of freedom (df equal to 1 and 5, respectively) related to testing either hypothesis.

  • Is it justified to assume that there is one common odds ratio? Why or why not?

  • Find the estimated common odds ratio and its confidence interval. Compare this adjusted odds ratio with the answer from question b and with the odds ratios in the age groups.

    • Code

    mantelhaen.test(crosstab_strat)
BreslowDayTest(crosstab_strat)

    Hints

    You can calculate the Mantel-Haenszel statistic using the function mantelhaen.test().

    You can use the Breslow-Day test to test for homogeneity of the odds ratios, for example with the BreslowDayTest() function from the DescTools package.

    In question c, you have already written the code to extract the statistics for the test for conditional independence, as well as the adjusted odds ratio and its confidence interval.

    Output

    mantelhaen.test(crosstab_strat)
    ## 
##  Mantel-Haenszel chi-squared test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  crosstab_strat
## Mantel-Haenszel X-squared = 83.215, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true common odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  3.562131 7.467743
## sample estimates:
## common odds ratio 
##          5.157623
    BreslowDayTest(crosstab_strat)
    ## 
##  Breslow-Day test on Homogeneity of Odds Ratios
## 
## data:  crosstab_strat
## X-squared = 9.3234, df = 5, p-value = 0.09684

    Discussion

    As you can see in the Mantel-Haenszel output, the common adjusted odds ratio is 5.16 (95% confidence interval 3.56-7.47). This is a bit lower than the crude odds ratio of 5.64 (question b). If you look at the cross tables from question c, you can see that this probably has to do with the unequal distribution of age. Most patients are in age category 3 and 4 which also have the highest odds ratios.

    The null hypothesis for “Conditional Independence” is testing whether the odds ratio is equal to 1 in each of the subgroups. Put it otherwise: it tests whether x and y are conditionally independent, \(OR_{xy}(k)=1\) for \(k=1,2,...,k\). Therefore, only one parameter is estimated and only 1 degree of freedom is used. If you look at the Mantel-Haenszel output, you can see that the p-value is < 2.2e-16, so H0 is rejected (\(OR_{xy}\) is not equal to 1).

    The null hypothesis for “Homogeneity” is that the association, and thus the odds ratio, is homogeneous across groups. Put it otherwise: it tests whether there is a homogeneous x-y association, \(OR_{xy}(1)=OR_{xy}(2)=...=OR_{xy}(k)\), with \(df=k-1\) (in this case 5). If you look at the output from the Breslow-Day test, you can see that the p-value is 0.097, which means that H0 is not rejected. You can assume that there is one common odds ratio.

    Practical exercise 24: Direct pooling in a meta-analysis

    At a certain stage in the course of an IVF (in vitro fertilisation) treatment an agonist or an antagonist is administered. In the table below the results are given of three clinical trials in which the use of an agonist was compared with an antagonist with respect to the ongoing (= at least for 12 weeks) pregnancy rate. 

    ## 
## 
## Table: Trial 1
## 
##                           antagonist (Ganirelix)   agonist (Busereline) 
## ------------------------  -----------------------  ---------------------
## no. patients              487                      243                  
## no. ongoing pregnancies   99                       62                   
## 
## 
## Table: Trial 2
## 
##                           antagonist (Ganirelix)   agonist (Busereline) 
## ------------------------  -----------------------  ---------------------
## no. patients              188                      85                   
## no. ongoing pregnancies   51                       28                   
## 
## 
## Table: Trial 3
## 
##                           antagonist (Ganirelix)   agonist (Busereline) 
## ------------------------  -----------------------  ---------------------
## no. patients              115                      36                   
## no. ongoing pregnancies   26                       11

    As effect measure we use the risk difference, i.e. the difference in pregnancy rate between both treatments. To analyse the data, we use the “pooling with inverse squared standard errors” method. We recommend to do the computations by hand, using a calculator. However, it is also possible to use R as a kind of pocket calculator. If you choose to use R, open the data file IVF.SAV.

    Question a

    Compute variables for the risks and risk differences of the trials. Also compute the weights and the weighted risk differences.

    Code

    ivf <- read.spss("./data/IVF.sav", to.data.frame = TRUE)
ivf  # print the data frame

# compute risks of pregnancy in both the antagonist (anta) and the agonist(agon) group
ivf$riskanta <- ivf$ANTAPREG / ivf$ANTA  # risk among anta are stored as the new variable riskanta
ivf$riskago <- ivf$AGONPREG / ivf$AGON   # risk among agon are stored as the new variable riskago
ivf[, c("riskanta", "riskago")]          # print the risks

# compute risk difference, its SE and weight
ivf$riskdiff <- ivf$riskago - ivf$riskanta   # calculate the risk differences between agon vs anta
ivf$se_diff <- sqrt(ivf$riskanta * (1 - ivf$riskanta) / 
                       ivf$ANTA + ivf$riskago * (1 - ivf$riskago) / ivf$AGON) #calculate the SE of the risk difference
ivf$weight <- 1 / ivf$se_diff ^ 2         # calculate the weight
ivf[, c("riskdiff", "se_diff", "weight")] # print the new variables

# computing weighted risk differences for each trial
ivf$riskdiff_weighted <- ivf$riskdiff * ivf$weight
ivf[, "riskdiff_weighted"] # print the value 

sum_weight <- sum(ivf$weight)
sum_weight
sum_riskdiff_weighted <- sum(ivf$riskdiff_weighted)
sum_riskdiff_weighted

    Hints

    The following variables are needed for all three trials: the risk differences between agonist and antagonist, their standard errors and weights.
    You can use the sum() function to get the sum of the weights and weighted risk differences.

    Output

    Discussion

    We observe that in the three trials, the group receiving an agonist had a higher risk of pregnancy than the antagonist group. The risk was 5.18%, 5.81% and 7.94% higher for trial 1, 2 and 3 respectively. The calculated weights don’t have a meaningful interpretation for now, but we can observe that trial 1 has the biggest weight and this corresponds to the biggest sample size compared to the other two trials. These weights will help us calculate the pooled risk difference in the following question.

    Question b

    Use the sums calculated in question a to create new variables: pooled risk difference and its standard error. Of course these variables are constant for the three trials. What is the associated approximate 95% confidence interval?

    Code

    riskdiff_pool <- sum_riskdiff_weighted / sum_weight
riskdiff_pool

se_riskdiff_pool <- sqrt(1 / sum_weight)
se_riskdiff_pool

riskdiff_pool_low <- riskdiff_pool - 1.96 * se_riskdiff_pool
riskdiff_pool_low 
riskdiff_pool_up  <- riskdiff_pool + 1.96 * se_riskdiff_pool
riskdiff_pool_up

    Hints

    First, to calculate the pooled risk difference you will want to divide the sum_riskdiff_weighted over the sum_weight. Second, calculate the SE by calculating the squared root (sqrt) of 1 over the sum_weight. Last, use the pooled risk difference and SE you just calculated to estimate de lower and upper confidence intervals.

    Output

    riskdiff_pool <- sum_riskdiff_weighted / sum_weight
riskdiff_pool
    ## [1] 0.0560262
    se_riskdiff_pool <- sqrt(1 / sum_weight)
se_riskdiff_pool
    ## [1] 0.02767186
    riskdiff_pool_low <- riskdiff_pool - 1.96 * se_riskdiff_pool
riskdiff_pool_low 
    ## [1] 0.001789362
    riskdiff_pool_up  <- riskdiff_pool + 1.96 * se_riskdiff_pool
riskdiff_pool_up
    ## [1] 0.110263

    Discussion

    When we pool the three trials, we observe that the group receiving an agonist had a 5.60% (95% confidence interval 0.18% - 11.02%) higher risk of pregnancy than the antagonist group.

    Question c

    Test the hypothesis of homogeneity of risk differences. State your conclusion.

    Code

    ivf$test_h0    <- (ivf$riskdiff - riskdiff_pool) ^ 2 / ivf$se_diff ^ 2
test_statistic <- sum(ivf$test_h0)
test_statistic

    Hints

    The null hypothesis is riskdiff_1 = riskdiff_2 = riskdiff_3. The test statistic is the sum of test_h0.

    Output

    ivf$test_h0    <- (ivf$riskdiff - riskdiff_pool) ^ 2 / ivf$se_diff ^ 2
test_statistic <- sum(ivf$test_h0)
test_statistic
    ## [1] 0.09090654

    Discussion

    The null hypothesis states that the risk differences across trials are homogeneous. The test statistic is the sum of test_h0, so 0.09 in this example. The distribution is Chi-square with k-1 df. If you look in the table, 0.09 with 2 df implies p>0.05 so the null hypothesis is not rejected, i.e. risk differences are homogeneous.

    Discussion

    This data frame consists of 13 columns and 111 rows. Every row represents an individual included in the study. From the total 111 subjects included, 52 were censored during follow-up and 59 (53%) died. The subjects were followed for a median of 4.12 years (IQR: 2.52 - 7.35).

    Extra tip: usually you will have to calculate the follow-up time using the date of entering the study and the date of event/censoring. Once you have calculated the time - for example by subtracting the latest minus the earliest date - make sure you describe the variable before using it. Having negative times or extreme outliers might be telling you that something was wrong in the dates of that observation. Not fixing this beforehand can lead to future problems when you start with the survival analysis.

    Question b

    Make a Kaplan-Meier (KM) life table for the whole group of 111 patients. You can do this using the survival package.
    What is the estimated two-year survival percentage with 95% confidence interval? If possible, read from the table the 25th, the 50th and the 75th percentile of the survival time. Check that the 50th percentile is the same as the median mentioned below the survival table. The mean survival time is not very useful because of its rather artificial interpretation, why?

    Code

    fit <- survfit(Surv(SURV, STATUS) ~ 1, data = survival) #create the table
summary(fit) #print the table

    Hints

    To create the Kaplan-Meier (KM) life table you have to fit a model using the survfit() function. Inside the function you will need to specify the time and status variable: survfit(Surv(SURV, STATUS) ~ 1, data = survival). By default, the function will consider the status coded as 1 as the event and 0 as the censored. Save the model as an object and use the summary() function to obtain the KM life table.

    To identify the two-year survival probability, follow to the time column and look for the row that points the last time before 2 years (in this case time point 1.87). To identify the time of 75th and 50th percentile of survival, follow the column with the survival probability to get to the closest values to 0.75 and 0.5 and look at the time point in the corresponding row. The 50th percentile will correspond to the median time. The 25th percentile of survival cannot be estimated because more than 25% survived until the end of follow-up.

    Question c

    Make a plot of the survival curve. What do the +'s mean?

    Code

    ggsurvplot(fit)

    Hints

    To graph the Kaplan Meier curve, use the ggsurvplot() function. You only need to include the name of object with the fitted model we used before.

    As you can see, by default the graph presents the survival curve with confidence intervals.

    Output

    ggsurvplot(fit)

    Discussion

    The graph represents the table we previously described. If we follow the Y axis until the survival probability of 0.50 and look in the graph to the corresponding time point on the X axis, we can see that the median time of survival is around 6 years.

    The ‘+’ represents the individuals censored at each time point.

    Question d

    In this part of the exercise we are going to explore different characteristics to add to the previous graph. Add a risk table that counts how many people were still alive at the intervals graphed. Draw a line to clearly identify the median survival time and explore different colours for the curves.

    Code

    ggsurvplot(fit,                  # plot a list of survfit objects
       conf.int = TRUE,          # include the confidence interval
       risk.table = TRUE,        # add a risk table
       surv.median.line = "hv",  # add the medicaun survival line 
       palette = c("#91D1C2B2")) # change the colour of the line

    Hints

    You can add different arguments inside the ggsurvplot() function to personalize the graph. The 95% confidence limits of the survival function are graphed by the argument conf.int = TRUE, this is the default. The number of individuals at risk by time can be obtained using the risk.table = TRUE argument. The line that helps you identify the median survival time is created by the argument surv.median.line. Allowed values include one of c("none", "hv", "h", "v"), where v: vertical, h:horizontal and hv:both. To change the colour, use the palette argument and the colour names from ggplot.

    Output

    ggsurvplot(fit,                  # plot a list of survfit objects
       conf.int = TRUE,          # include the confidence interval
       risk.table = TRUE,        # add a risk table
       surv.median.line = "hv",  # add the medicaun survival line 
       palette = c("#91D1C2B2")) # change the colour of the line

    Question e

    The actuarial method differs from the Kaplan-Meier method by taking larger intervals. The number and width of the intervals can be chosen by yourself. Make an actuarial life table, specifying intervals of one year (0 through 11 by 1). Also ask for a plot of the survival and hazard function. Study carefully the output of the life table. The proportion surviving, which stands for the estimated conditional probability of surviving an interval, is computed as (1 the number of events/number of patients at risk), where the patients censored during the interval are counted as half the interval at risk.

    Code

    summary(fit, times = c(0:11))

hazard <- summary(fit, times = c(0:11))$n.event / summary(fit, times = c(0:11))$n.risk
plot(summary(fit, times = c(0:11))$time - 1 , hazard, type = "p", ylab = "Hazard", xlab = "Survival since operation (years)", xlim = c(0:10))

    Hints

    To create the actuarial table, the simplest way is to add a time argument when evaluating the summary of the fitted model. We can do this by defining the specific time as a vector c(0:11).

    Subsequently, in order to create the hazard plot, you need to calculate the hazard at each time point: number of events / number of people at risk. After that, you can plot the hazard against the survival time since operation using the plot function. type = "p" will give a plot with points of the hazard at each time point.

    Output

    Hints

    To create curves for different groups, add the factor variable in the survfit model, after the ~, save it as a new model. These arguments are risk.table.col = "strata" to add a risk table by groups, risk.table.height will adapt the size of the risk table, in case you have many groups you will want to increase the height of it. linetype = "strata" creates the median survival lines for each group. Finally, you may have to add the colours you need for the different groups if you intend to use palette.

    To obtain the log-rank test you need to use the survdiff function, the expression of the model will be the same as with survfit.

    Discussion

    The null hypothesis that the survival distribution is equal among men and women cannot be rejected. The median survival time for women was 6.06 years and 8.87 for men. We observe graphically that the curves cross and confidence intervals overlap and the log rank test p-value was 0.31. We can also say that at 10 years from follow up, the survival probability for men is 32.27% (95% CI: 20.58 - 50.60%) and for women is 45.04% (95% CI: 31.21 - 64.99%).

    We observe that the survival curves for the different tumour locations are very similar and the survival probability is not different between groups (p = 0.41).

    Regarding the Duke criteria, we observe that the survival probability decreases with an increasing tumour stage. The estimated survival probability at 10 years for group A at baseline is 54.1% (95% CI 35.5 - 76.6%), 45.78% for group B (95% CI: 33.43 - 62.39%), and 7.45% for group C (95% CI: 1.20 - 46.08%).

    Question g

    To look whether age at operation is a prognostic factor, categorise age in above 60 years and 60 years or younger. Inspect the two survival curves. Test equality with the log rank test. Express the difference between the curves by the hazard ratio (relative risk) using a Cox proportional hazards model. In the output the estimate of the hazard ratio is given under exp(coef).

    Code

    survival <- survival %>%
  mutate(age_cat = ifelse(AGE <= 60, 0, 1))

fit_age <- survfit(Surv(SURV, STATUS) ~ age_cat, data = survival)
ggsurvplot(fit_age,
         conf.int = TRUE,
       risk.table = TRUE,
       risk.table.col = "strata",
       risk.table.height = 0.3,
       surv.median.line = "hv",
       linetype = "strata",
       palette = c("#E7B800", "#2E9FDF"),
       legend.labs = c("<= 60", "> 60"))

cox_age <- coxph(Surv(SURV, STATUS) ~ age_cat, data = survival)
cox_age

    Hints

    First create a variable with age categories, define 0 if AGE <= 60, else 1, here we will use the mutate and ifelse function from the dplyr package, but you can do it in the way you want! Second, fit the model using survfit and our new categorical variable for age, draw the curves using ggsurvplot. Finally, to fit the Cox model we will use the coxph function, which will use the same specifications as with survfit, save it as a new object and see what the saved model contains.

    Output

    survival <- survival %>%
  mutate(age_cat = ifelse(AGE <= 60, 0, 1)) 

fit_age <- survfit(Surv(SURV, STATUS) ~ age_cat, data = survival)
summary(fit_age, time = c(10))

ggsurvplot(fit_age,
         conf.int = TRUE,
       risk.table = TRUE,
       risk.table.col = "strata",
       risk.table.height = 0.3,
       surv.median.line = "hv",
        linetype = "strata",
      palette = c("#E7B800", "#2E9FDF"),
       legend.labs = c("<= 60", "> 60"))

cox_age <- coxph(Surv(SURV, STATUS) ~ age_cat, data = survival)
cox_age

    Discussion

    Subjects 60 years old or younger have a survival probability at ten years of 68.9% (95% CI: 55.1 - 86.3%) compared to 23.5% (95% CI: 12.8 - 42.9%) among the subjects above 60 years at 10 years of follow-up. We can also say that the patients above 60 years have 2.5 times the risk of dying during the complete follow-up period compared to the patients who are 60 years old or younger.
